1
00:01:39,625 --> 00:01:41,583
[IWASHITA]
Three Sacred Treasures, huh?

2
00:01:41,666 --> 00:01:42,958
[YOSHINO]
Right!

3
00:01:43,041 --> 00:01:46,250
The Staff, the Hanging Drum,
and the Golden Dragon.

4
00:01:46,333 --> 00:01:47,958
We need to revive the festival.

5
00:01:48,041 --> 00:01:49,916
We have to have
the treasures to do that.

6
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:51,541
Any idea where they could be?

7
00:01:52,583 --> 00:01:55,083
It's fifty years
since the last festival.

8
00:01:55,166 --> 00:01:57,708
The priest passed away
a long time ago,

9
00:01:57,791 --> 00:02:00,125
and even the shrine
itself is gone.

10
00:02:00,208 --> 00:02:02,083
Our work is cut
out for us, huh?

11
00:02:06,250 --> 00:02:08,291
Tell me! Did your
grandma know anything?

12
00:02:08,375 --> 00:02:10,000
Unfortunately not.

13
00:02:10,083 --> 00:02:11,333
Oh, no!

14
00:02:11,416 --> 00:02:12,958
My grandma and grandpa
said that they don't

15
00:02:13,041 --> 00:02:15,875
remember anything about
the festival treasures either.

16
00:02:15,958 --> 00:02:18,125
I guess we'll make our own.

17
00:02:18,208 --> 00:02:20,291
It's not DIY.

18
00:02:20,375 --> 00:02:22,750
[NOGE] I would bet the
professor might know.

19
00:02:22,833 --> 00:02:23,791
What professor?

20
00:02:23,875 --> 00:02:25,625
We get a lot
of orders from him.

21
00:02:25,708 --> 00:02:28,166
I heard he used to teach
at some college.

22
00:02:28,250 --> 00:02:29,416
Let's see.

23
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:30,666
Ah, here we go.

24
00:02:32,458 --> 00:02:34,041
He's the one who
wrote this book.

25
00:02:34,125 --> 00:02:35,708
"Cultural Anthropology."

26
00:02:35,791 --> 00:02:37,041
Oh!

27
00:02:37,125 --> 00:02:39,291
This was once my textbook
for a college course.

28
00:02:39,375 --> 00:02:40,416
What a small world.

29
00:02:40,500 --> 00:02:43,250
Wow, and he lives in Manoyama?

30
00:02:43,333 --> 00:02:45,583
He lives by himself
in Warabiya Village

31
00:02:45,666 --> 00:02:46,666
out in the mountains.

32
00:02:46,750 --> 00:02:49,208
But, he's quite an
eccentric old man.

33
00:02:49,291 --> 00:02:50,541
I'm intrigued.

34
00:02:50,625 --> 00:02:51,875
Should we go?

35
00:02:51,958 --> 00:02:54,291
Warabiya is pretty deep in
the mountains, you know.

36
00:02:58,916 --> 00:03:01,250
[YOSHINO]
It's my first time out this far.

37
00:03:01,333 --> 00:03:03,708
It must be hard living
in a place like this.

38
00:03:03,791 --> 00:03:05,958
Yeah, makes you wonder
where they go shopping.

39
00:03:13,875 --> 00:03:16,083
[YOSHINO]
Excuse me! Mr. Suzuhara?

40
00:03:17,708 --> 00:03:18,958
Are you at home, sir?

41
00:03:20,625 --> 00:03:21,750
Maybe he's out.

42
00:03:23,875 --> 00:03:24,833
[GROUP gasps]

43
00:03:24,916 --> 00:03:26,375
That was scary.

44
00:03:26,458 --> 00:03:28,541
[SUZUHARA]
Well, well, look at that.

45
00:03:28,625 --> 00:03:30,958
Five sneaky tanukis at my door.

46
00:03:32,083 --> 00:03:33,416
Can I help you?

47
00:03:35,833 --> 00:03:38,250
Just to be clear,
did he call us tanukis?

48
00:03:38,333 --> 00:03:40,041
[MAKI]
Yes. Yes, he did.

49
00:03:40,125 --> 00:03:41,666
[SHIORI] I have a feeling
he might know a lot

50
00:03:41,750 --> 00:03:43,291
about the past, though.

51
00:03:43,375 --> 00:03:45,375
Cultural anthropology.

52
00:03:45,458 --> 00:03:48,500
It involves taking up residence
in the region being researched,

53
00:03:48,583 --> 00:03:50,250
and observing its
culture and society

54
00:03:50,333 --> 00:03:52,041
over a long period of time.

55
00:03:52,125 --> 00:03:53,458
[SUZUHARA]
Exactly.

56
00:03:53,541 --> 00:03:56,125
Rather than tracing
back to the past,

57
00:03:56,208 --> 00:03:59,416
this field focuses solely
on knowing the present.

58
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:01,208
Anybody care for a drink?

59
00:04:01,291 --> 00:04:03,000
[MAKI]
We're all fine, thanks, though.

60
00:04:03,083 --> 00:04:04,625
That was a joke.

61
00:04:04,708 --> 00:04:06,958
This stuff would be
wasted on tanukis.

62
00:04:10,291 --> 00:04:13,125
I'm hosting the queen
and her ministers, am I?

63
00:04:13,208 --> 00:04:14,625
Oh, you've heard of us, then?

64
00:04:14,708 --> 00:04:16,625
[SUZUHARA] I saw you on
"Moving Mountains."

65
00:04:16,708 --> 00:04:19,333
Playing at your little
rural revival games.

66
00:04:19,416 --> 00:04:20,750
What do you mean by "games"?

67
00:04:20,833 --> 00:04:22,833
We take our work very seriously!

68
00:04:22,916 --> 00:04:24,375
Hey, it's okay, Shiori.

69
00:04:24,458 --> 00:04:26,291
[SUZUHARA] And you're here
to ask about the festival

70
00:04:26,375 --> 00:04:28,416
that ended fifty years ago, huh?

71
00:04:28,500 --> 00:04:29,916
Yes, sir!

72
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,958
The five of us are committed
to trying to bring it back!

73
00:04:32,041 --> 00:04:33,458
That's interesting.

74
00:04:33,541 --> 00:04:37,125
Unfortunately, I only moved to
Manoyama twenty years ago.

75
00:04:37,208 --> 00:04:38,625
What are you aiming
to accomplish

76
00:04:38,708 --> 00:04:40,541
by reviving it, anyhow?

77
00:04:40,625 --> 00:04:41,583
[YOSHINO]
Uhh...

78
00:04:41,666 --> 00:04:43,166
Remember, it didn't
end on its own.

79
00:04:43,250 --> 00:04:46,083
The fact it ended means
no one cared about it.

80
00:04:46,166 --> 00:04:47,291
Don't you agree?

81
00:04:48,500 --> 00:04:50,041
No, I actually don't.

82
00:04:50,125 --> 00:04:52,083
I think the people
really need it.

83
00:04:52,166 --> 00:04:53,875
They need a place to return to.

84
00:04:53,958 --> 00:04:55,041
A place to gather.

85
00:04:57,166 --> 00:04:58,500
C'mon, Let's go.

86
00:04:58,583 --> 00:05:01,125
It seems to me like this
professor doesn't know anything.

87
00:05:02,541 --> 00:05:04,833
[SUZUHARA]
I never said I didn't know.

88
00:05:04,916 --> 00:05:07,500
I've heard rumors in the
village, over the years.

89
00:05:07,583 --> 00:05:09,416
Apparently, one of
the treasures is held

90
00:05:09,500 --> 00:05:12,000
in the storehouse of a
certain traditional home.

91
00:05:13,166 --> 00:05:14,791
[MAKI] If he knew,
he should've just told us

92
00:05:14,875 --> 00:05:16,166
from the start!

93
00:05:16,250 --> 00:05:18,333
I really can't stand
people like that.

94
00:05:18,416 --> 00:05:19,875
He reminds me of someone.

95
00:05:19,958 --> 00:05:21,291
What're we gonna do?

96
00:05:21,375 --> 00:05:23,541
There are so many
storehouses around here.

97
00:05:23,625 --> 00:05:25,458
We're just gonna
have to check at each one.

98
00:05:27,625 --> 00:05:28,583
[SANAE]
Hm?

99
00:05:29,625 --> 00:05:30,583
[YOSHINO]
Sanae!

100
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:58,416
[SUZUHARA] I think I'll play a
little game with those tanukis.

101
00:05:59,625 --> 00:06:03,458
[GROUP chattering]

102
00:06:03,541 --> 00:06:05,708
Hey! Isn't that Takamizawa?

103
00:06:06,833 --> 00:06:08,166
[TAKAMIZAWA]
Yeah.

104
00:06:08,250 --> 00:06:10,333
I've tried talking to my company
about it several times!

105
00:06:10,416 --> 00:06:11,916
[SHIGE] You do understand
what you're doing,

106
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:13,666
taking away our
freedom like this?

107
00:06:13,750 --> 00:06:16,208
[GORO] And what about those
of us that live alone, hm?

108
00:06:16,291 --> 00:06:17,708
I had thought you understood

109
00:06:17,791 --> 00:06:20,250
and were on our side
about this, Takamizawa.

110
00:06:20,333 --> 00:06:21,625
I'm disappointed.

111
00:06:21,708 --> 00:06:23,458
[TAKAMIZAWA] Come on,
please don't say that, Kiyo!

112
00:06:23,541 --> 00:06:24,666
I wonder what's up.

113
00:06:24,750 --> 00:06:26,166
From what I've heard, this area

114
00:06:26,250 --> 00:06:28,791
is about to be removed from
the current bus route.

115
00:06:28,875 --> 00:06:30,666
People are upset.

116
00:06:30,750 --> 00:06:31,750
[YOSHINO]
Oh, wow.

117
00:06:33,125 --> 00:06:34,583
[MASA]
Please forgive the mess.

118
00:06:34,666 --> 00:06:37,833
I haven't given the storehouse
a proper cleaning for years!

119
00:06:37,916 --> 00:06:39,875
Oh, and if you see
any naughty mags,

120
00:06:39,958 --> 00:06:41,083
just pretend you didn't!

121
00:06:41,166 --> 00:06:43,166
[laughs]

122
00:06:43,250 --> 00:06:44,916
Masa, what is that? A tablet?

123
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:46,916
Oh, this thing?

124
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:48,833
Someone from the
city offices left it here

125
00:06:48,916 --> 00:06:50,041
a little while back.

126
00:06:50,125 --> 00:06:52,000
I have no clue
how to use it,

127
00:06:52,083 --> 00:06:54,708
but it's pretty helpful for
night time bathroom trips.

128
00:06:54,791 --> 00:06:56,125
Oops! The batteries!

129
00:06:56,208 --> 00:06:58,125
[SANAE yelps]
Someone just touched my butt!

130
00:06:58,208 --> 00:06:59,041
[RIRIKO]
It wasn't me.

131
00:06:59,125 --> 00:07:00,125
[MASA]
Me neither!

132
00:07:01,125 --> 00:07:02,541
[MAKI]
Hide, hello sir.

133
00:07:02,625 --> 00:07:04,041
[SHIORI] Thanks so much
for letting us look through

134
00:07:04,125 --> 00:07:05,250
your storehouse!

135
00:07:05,333 --> 00:07:07,208
Sure thing. Did you
find what you needed?

136
00:07:07,291 --> 00:07:08,875
[SHIORI]
I'm afraid not.

137
00:07:08,958 --> 00:07:09,958
That's too bad.

138
00:07:10,041 --> 00:07:12,125
I'm sorry that I
couldn't be more help.

139
00:07:12,208 --> 00:07:14,208
Not at all! We appreciate it!

140
00:07:14,291 --> 00:07:16,041
Are you fixing
one of your tools?

141
00:07:16,125 --> 00:07:17,500
You still enjoy work, don't you?

142
00:07:17,583 --> 00:07:20,791
Oh, no, I've been retired
for quite some time now.

143
00:07:20,875 --> 00:07:23,458
I'm just keeping up
the routine at this point.

144
00:07:23,541 --> 00:07:25,666
It can be a hard habit
to break, you know.

145
00:07:25,750 --> 00:07:28,541
I made my living
this way for decades.

146
00:07:28,625 --> 00:07:29,833
Of course, makes sense!

147
00:07:29,916 --> 00:07:30,833
[timer beeping]

148
00:07:30,916 --> 00:07:31,833
[HIDE]
Oh, good!

149
00:07:31,916 --> 00:07:33,458
It's time for lunch!

150
00:07:33,541 --> 00:07:34,958
So, you use the...?

151
00:07:35,041 --> 00:07:36,291
It's very useful.

152
00:07:36,375 --> 00:07:38,416
It works as a timer,
and as a weight!

153
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:40,041
Yep, they're useful, all right!

154
00:07:41,458 --> 00:07:42,791
[door opens]

155
00:07:42,875 --> 00:07:44,291
[YOSHINO]
I'm a hungry girl!

156
00:07:44,375 --> 00:07:46,041
Oh, hey, Takamizawa!

157
00:07:46,125 --> 00:07:47,083
[TAKAMIZAWA]
Hey!

158
00:07:48,791 --> 00:07:51,916
[ERIKA] Lunch A: Tonkatsu.
Lunch B: Hot Somen.

159
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:53,666
--[YOSHINO] I'll go with "A."
--[MAKI] Same here.

160
00:07:53,750 --> 00:07:54,875
I'll take "B," please.

161
00:07:54,958 --> 00:07:56,625
[SANAE]
"B" for me, too.

162
00:07:56,708 --> 00:07:58,875
--Curry.
--'Kay.

163
00:07:58,958 --> 00:07:59,833
[sighs]

164
00:07:59,916 --> 00:08:01,250
[YOSHINO]
Takamizawa!

165
00:08:01,333 --> 00:08:02,041
[TAKAMIZAWA]
Huh?

166
00:08:02,125 --> 00:08:03,416
We saw you the other day.

167
00:08:03,500 --> 00:08:04,750
That looked rough.

168
00:08:04,833 --> 00:08:07,083
Oh, yeah, that's okay.

169
00:08:07,166 --> 00:08:09,208
There's nothing I can
do about it, anyway.

170
00:08:09,291 --> 00:08:10,625
I understand.

171
00:08:10,708 --> 00:08:13,041
But what happens if those stops
are taken off the route?

172
00:08:13,125 --> 00:08:15,500
I think in cases like this
they usually replace it

173
00:08:15,583 --> 00:08:17,583
with a subsidized
community bus.

174
00:08:17,666 --> 00:08:19,750
So things won't actually
change much, then?

175
00:08:19,833 --> 00:08:22,416
[TAKAMIZAWA] Well, the local
government isn't exactly rich.

176
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:25,625
Running just one bus for a year
costs over ten million yen.

177
00:08:25,708 --> 00:08:26,750
That much?

178
00:08:26,833 --> 00:08:28,666
And we only get
about ten riders a day

179
00:08:28,750 --> 00:08:30,166
from Warabiya Village.

180
00:08:30,250 --> 00:08:33,125
Not that they don't matter,
because they do, but

181
00:08:33,208 --> 00:08:35,416
the buses aren't
the only problem, here.

182
00:08:35,500 --> 00:08:37,333
I mean, there's no hope
of the town growing

183
00:08:37,416 --> 00:08:38,750
at this point.

184
00:08:38,833 --> 00:08:41,125
They just have to make
sure to live within their means

185
00:08:41,208 --> 00:08:42,625
from here on out.

186
00:08:42,708 --> 00:08:44,208
That sounds so harsh.

187
00:08:44,291 --> 00:08:46,708
You guys only talk
about boring stuff.

188
00:08:46,791 --> 00:08:49,625
That's why I want to get
out of this stupid little town.

189
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:59,583
[USHIMATSU coughing]

190
00:08:59,666 --> 00:09:00,416
Old ass!

191
00:09:00,500 --> 00:09:03,208
[coughing]

192
00:09:03,291 --> 00:09:06,500
[sighs] Damn, I thought
I might die, there.

193
00:09:06,583 --> 00:09:09,250
So. What do you
want with me, anyway?

194
00:09:09,333 --> 00:09:11,208
[CHITOSE]
You just keep hanging on, huh?

195
00:09:11,291 --> 00:09:12,458
[USHIMATSU]
You show up out of nowhere

196
00:09:12,541 --> 00:09:13,916
and greet me like that?

197
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:15,125
[CHITOSE yells]

198
00:09:15,208 --> 00:09:18,083
I won't be back!
Hurry up and die, already!

199
00:09:18,166 --> 00:09:19,458
[USHIMATSU]
What the hell?

200
00:09:20,875 --> 00:09:23,625
[GORO] This bus thing's
a total catastrophe.

201
00:09:23,708 --> 00:09:25,583
If I start using taxis now,

202
00:09:25,666 --> 00:09:27,416
I'm going to be broke
in no time.

203
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:29,333
We'll worry about that later.

204
00:09:29,416 --> 00:09:31,208
Those of us who can
drive will be flexible

205
00:09:31,291 --> 00:09:32,458
and help each other out.

206
00:09:32,541 --> 00:09:35,375
[GORO] Masa, you can
barely see at night!

207
00:09:35,458 --> 00:09:37,291
You shouldn't be driving at all!

208
00:09:37,375 --> 00:09:39,875
I still seem to have a
sixth sense for butts, though!

209
00:09:39,958 --> 00:09:42,291
[GROUP laughs]

210
00:09:43,250 --> 00:09:44,916
They were standing
around by the door,

211
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,041
so I brought them in.

212
00:09:46,125 --> 00:09:47,625
Is that okay, Professor?

213
00:09:47,708 --> 00:09:51,208
Of course.
Everyone, the queen is here.

214
00:09:51,291 --> 00:09:52,333
Thanks very much.

215
00:09:52,416 --> 00:09:53,583
It's nice to meet you all.

216
00:09:53,666 --> 00:09:55,583
Ah! I saw you on TV once!

217
00:09:55,666 --> 00:09:58,000
That other girl's from
<i>The Oden Detective</i> !

218
00:09:58,083 --> 00:10:00,125
Kids these days
are remarkable.

219
00:10:00,208 --> 00:10:02,500
The one with the glasses
is my type o' lady.

220
00:10:02,583 --> 00:10:03,833
Talk about a caboose.

221
00:10:03,916 --> 00:10:06,041
It was you, old bastard.

222
00:10:06,125 --> 00:10:08,833
So, what brings
you all here today?

223
00:10:08,916 --> 00:10:11,625
Well, I don't look the part,
but I am the queen,

224
00:10:11,708 --> 00:10:12,958
so I thought I should
learn more about

225
00:10:13,041 --> 00:10:14,708
how different people live here.

226
00:10:14,791 --> 00:10:16,875
[SUZUHARA]
Hmm. Interesting.

227
00:10:16,958 --> 00:10:19,125
As I assume
you're well aware,

228
00:10:19,208 --> 00:10:20,875
the bus will stop
coming around here

229
00:10:20,958 --> 00:10:22,458
before much longer.

230
00:10:22,541 --> 00:10:24,875
We want to stop
that from happening.

231
00:10:24,958 --> 00:10:26,291
What do you think?

232
00:10:26,375 --> 00:10:28,291
We want to hear young
people's thoughts.

233
00:10:28,375 --> 00:10:29,750
You first, Ms. Koharu.

234
00:10:29,833 --> 00:10:31,541
Uh... Oh, umm...

235
00:10:31,625 --> 00:10:34,208
If they drive slow and
focus on efficiency--

236
00:10:34,291 --> 00:10:36,750
That's an "F."
A truly pointless effort.

237
00:10:36,833 --> 00:10:38,416
Next, Ms. Shinomiya.

238
00:10:38,500 --> 00:10:41,833
Increase fares so that
they don't operate at a loss,

239
00:10:41,916 --> 00:10:42,625
I guess?

240
00:10:42,708 --> 00:10:44,208
[SUZUHARA]
Fail.

241
00:10:44,291 --> 00:10:47,041
Any and all fare changes require
approval from the government.

242
00:10:47,125 --> 00:10:48,791
[SUZUHARA]
Next, Ms. Midorikawa.

243
00:10:48,875 --> 00:10:50,250
Make the buses smaller.

244
00:10:50,333 --> 00:10:51,541
[SUZUHARA]
That's a C minus.

245
00:10:51,625 --> 00:10:53,791
We still can't reduce
people's salaries.

246
00:10:53,875 --> 00:10:55,583
So what do we do, Ms. Oribe?

247
00:10:55,666 --> 00:10:58,333
Wait until self-driving cars
have finally become popular.

248
00:10:58,416 --> 00:10:59,583
That's an "F."

249
00:10:59,666 --> 00:11:02,041
We obviously won't be
alive when that happens.

250
00:11:02,125 --> 00:11:04,375
Last one. Ms. Kozuki.

251
00:11:04,458 --> 00:11:05,875
This affects the whole country.

252
00:11:05,958 --> 00:11:07,958
The decreasing population
problem isn't limited

253
00:11:08,041 --> 00:11:09,291
to our town.

254
